I did try it, and it worked, but I don't know how it would work before .ready is executed.

https://www.w3schools.com/jquery/jquery_syntax.asp says:

This is to prevent any jQuery code from running before the document is finished loading (is ready).

It is good practice to wait for the document to be fully loaded and ready before working with it. This also allows you to have your JavaScript code before the body of your document, in the head section. 

I think it would work in our case even if .ready has not been executed yet, which might what happened this morning when release was undefined. Why it had not been executed is a mystery though.

Yeah seems like it should be fine, the patch works on my end. This is probably the best solution, waiting until the content is ready before checking the (static) meta tag. I'm also just as confused as to why it never executed at all.

commits.commitMessage:
Adapt cloudsearch tools for a single search domain

Update various tools so that they upload to and access a single domain
with a "release" parameter specifying Legato version.

The version is autodetected from the text in aboutLegato.html.

Here is a bash function to backport the version meta tag to old releases
without regenerating:

```
function ensure_ver_tag() {local ver=$(grep -hoP "doc-version.*title=\"\K([^\"]+)"  $1/*.html); echo "Detected $ver";  for filename in $1/*.html; do;  ! grep -qF "content=\"$ver\"" "$filename"  &&  grep -qF "meta content=\"legato" "$filename" &&  echo "adding $ver tag to $filename" &&  sed -i -e "s|\(<meta content=\"legato, iot\" name=\"keywords\"/>\)|\1\n<meta content=\"$ver\" name=\"legato-version\"/>|g" "$filename"; done}
```

Run it with a dir e.g. `ensure_ver_tag .` to proccess all the files in it.

Resolves: LE-11456
Change-Id: I89185dfa7d2921a4db316c623e0e7719558fbe21
commits.subject: Adapt cloudsearch tools for a single search domain

commits.commitMessage:
Introduce KConfig for Legato build configuration

The KConfig settings subsume a number of disparate settings that were
previously controlled by various environment variables and preprocessor
defines.  The legacy environment variables are still used to populate
the initial values if no configuration is present, however the KConfig
output has become the single point of truth for these values going
forward.

The default behaviour of "make" and "make <target>" is preserved.  In
addition, "make menuconfig" and "make menuconfig_<target>" can be used
to explicitly change the configuration values.

The largest changes are the addition of the new KConfig files defining
the options, and extensive modifications to the Makefiles to generate
and use the configured values.  Most of the rest of the changes are
modifying preprocessor directives and values to use the new
configuration names.

Resolves: LE-10145 LE-10147
Change-Id: I179eb50c53021cf72a96a94275644e27fe137833
commits.subject: Introduce KConfig for Legato build configuration
